                    <span>Just bought this book five days ago and I couldn't put it down. If you love mysteries, if you love history and if you love the cat & mouse games of the Cold War you will love this non-fiction book. This book is well researched and worth the money you will pay for it.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">A long overdue history of the amber room</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      /
                      <span>6</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-05-26</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>As the saying goes: - 'who needs fiction with history like this'. At last the first non-fiction history of the Amber room. This is not the Berry book refered to above, but the first history in english of the famed Amber Rooms of the catherine palace, St Petersburg russia. The jewel of 18th century Russia had amber walls, valued by weight alone at $100-150million dollars. Originally based in Berlin, they were given as a gift to Peter the Great while on his great Tour of Europe in the early 18th century. Upon his return to russia, the amber panels lay in storage for some years. It was eventually the enlightened monarch Catherine the Great who ordered her gifted architect, Francesco Rastrelli to design a bigger and more magnificent ammber room in the longest palace in the world at Tsarskoye Selo outside St Petersburg. The room was then filled with magnificent amber objects. And there the room was to stay until 1941 when the Germans arrived at the palace. Although covered by the Russians with wall paper, the Germans discovered the room and shipped it to East Prussia's Koenigsberg Castle (now the Russian city of Kaliningrad) Nobody is really sure what happened the amber room, but it vanished in 1945, probably destroyed in the allied bombing. Fortunately the amber room is now fully restored, with help from the russian customs and German ruhr gas company. I was lucky enough to see it last year in time for the 300th anniversary. I always wanted a history in english but could only ever manage a few pamphlets in russian or German. This book will be treasured alongside my photos of the new Amber Room. If you want a gripping read.... then this is the book for u</span>
                  
              
